<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-133-169 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 838 692</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 10 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Thinking Machines claims speed record. (Thinking Machines Corp.'sCM-200, supercomputer) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Thinking Machines Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Thinking Machines CM-200 (Supercomputer) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSupercomputersComputer industryPerformance MeasurementProcessor SpeedParallel processing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>THINKING MACHINES CLAIMS SPEED RECORD 06/10/91 CAMBRIDGE, MASSACHUSETTS,U.S.A., 1991 JUN 10 (NB) -- Thinking Machines has introduced the CM-200, a100-user supercomputer that has captured the title of world's fastest inbenchmark tests.andP;  The parallel processing system can be set up with as manyas 64,000 processors.andM;Benchmark tests rated the CM-200 at 9.03 gigaflops (billion floating-pointoperations per second).andP;  That beats Intel's recently introduced TouchstoneDelta supercomputer, which clocks in at about 8.6 gigaflops.andP;  However, TimBrowne, a spokesman for Thinking Machines, downplayed the importance ofbenchmarks as opposed to the applications the machine actually makespossible.andM;Several CM-200 machines are already on order, Browne said.andP;  Among them areone that will be used for a variety of academic research and one that will beused in industrial work.andP;  Over its lifetime, Browne said, this sort ofsupercomputer line might sell 100 or so units.andP;  Full 64,000-processor versionof the CM-200 cost US$8 million to US$10 million.andM;Browne said a smaller version, with fewer processors and selling for aboutUS$300,000, is about to be announced.andM;(Grant Buckler/19910608/Press Contact: Tim Browne, Thinking Machines,617-234-5525)</TEXT></DOC>